          'The thermodynamic equation of a data center is straightforward: the IT load IS the cooling load. One kilowatt of IT power becomes one kilowatt of heat that must leave the building continuously, plus lighting (typically 0.5-1 W/ft² in a managed space), personnel heat (250 BTU/hr per person, negligible in unmanned halls), and building envelope gain (minimal in a well-insulated windowless room). The total: DATA CENTER DESIGN COOLING LOAD ≈ IT load × (1 + overhead fraction) where overhead fraction from the UPS, transformers, and switchgear losses is typically 0.05-0.10. PUE target is the engineer\'s efficiency promise embedded in this arithmetic from the first calculation.',
          'Chiller selection — the heart of a chilled water plant — involves four mechanical engineering decisions. CAPACITY: tons of refrigeration (1 ton = 12,000 BTU/hr = 3.517 kW), sized for the cooling load with N+1 redundancy. EFFICIENCY: COP (Coefficient of Performance = cooling output kW / input kW) and IPLV (Integrated Part-Load Value — the weighted average efficiency across all operating load points, more meaningful for data centers that rarely run at full load) — modern centrifugal chillers achieve COP 6.5-7.5 at design conditions. REFRIGERANT: the transition from legacy R-123 and R-134a to low-GWP alternatives (R-1234ze, R-513A) for new designs. CONDENSER TYPE: air-cooled chillers reject heat directly to the air (lower first cost, higher energy) vs water-cooled (condenser water from a cooling tower, higher efficiency but more plant).',
          'COOLING TOWERS complete the water-cooled plant: evaporative cooling removes heat from condenser water by evaporating a small fraction to the atmosphere. Design parameters: APPROACH TEMPERATURE (difference between leaving water temperature and outdoor wet-bulb — typically 3-7°F; a smaller approach means a larger, more expensive tower), RANGE (temperature difference between hot condenser water entering and cooled water leaving — typically 10°F), and DRIFT ELIMINATORS that capture entrained water droplets leaving the tower (a Legionella control and water conservation requirement). WATER TREATMENT (biocide, corrosion inhibitor, scale inhibitor, pH control) is an active chemical management program: ASHRAE Guideline 12 and ASHRAE 188 (Legionella risk management) are the engineering references, and a neglected tower is a Legionella liability and a fouled chiller waiting to happen.',
          'The PRIMARY-SECONDARY PUMPING architecture is the data center cooling standard: primary pumps circulate water through the chillers at constant flow (which the chillers require for stable operation), secondary pumps distribute variable flow to the CRAC/CRAH units (variable speed drives respond to pressure and load). A DIFFERENTIAL PRESSURE SENSOR at the far end of the distribution loop controls secondary VSD speed — the same control logic as any variable-flow hydronic system, now serving megawatts of IT load. The bypass valve between supply and return headers balances the primary flow when secondary demand is low. This architecture allows individual chillers to be isolated for maintenance while the plant serves load — concurrent maintainability at the mechanical plant level.',
